http://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Delhi/Court-sends-ink-attacker-to-one-day-police-custody/article14005581.ece

A Delhi court on Monday sent the woman who had allegedly thrown ink at Delhi Chief Minister Arvind Kejriwal to one-day police custody.The woman, Bhavna Arora, had allegedly thrown ink at Mr. Kejriwal on Sunday at a function where he was speaking at the Chhatrasal Stadium to celebrate the ‘success’ of the odd-even scheme.Metropolitan Magistrate Sunil Kumar remanded Bhavna Arora to police custody till Tuesday.Earlier, seeking her police remand, counsel for the police argued that her custodial interrogation was required to find out whether other persons were also involved in the incident.The police argued that the motive and whether she was involved in other cases were also to be ascertained.Seeking bail, counsel for Ms. Arora argued that the offence, if any, committed by her was not a serious one. She should be released on bail on the ground of being a woman, her counsel further argued.The woman had on Sunday claimed that she was a member of the splinter group of the Punjab unit of the Aam Aadmi Party. She also asserted that she was in possession of proof of an alleged ‘CNG scam’ linked to the odd-even scheme.Ms. Arora is a resident of Rama Vihar in Outer Delhi. The police have booked her under Sections 186 (obstructing public servant in discharge of his public functions) and 353 (assault or use criminal force to deter public servant from discharge of his duty) of the IPC.The police subjected Ms. Arora to custodial interrogation after securing her remand. During her interrogation, she reiterated the allegations made before the Press on the day of the incident.She purportedly claimed that after making several unsuccessful efforts to approach Mr. Kejriwal and even submitting written complaint, she decided to register her protest by throwing ink on him.Police said motive and whether she was involved in other cases were to be ascertained